{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cd7f9b00-708e-42c9-975f-d512d9070140","content":"## What happened\n\n`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS in newer .NET versions. Apple's native crypto frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) **do not support DSA**, and .NET dropped its OpenSSL-based fallback for macOS. Windows and Linux still work because they have native DSA support (CNG and OpenSSL respectively).\n\n## How to fix it\n\n**Option 1 – Use BouncyCastle (recommended for verify-only scenarios):**\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters publicKey)\n{\n    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\n    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\n    verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\n    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\nThis is a fully managed implementation—works on all platforms with no native dependencies.\n\n**Option 2 – Platform-conditional code** (if you want to keep using the built-in `DSA` on Windows/Linux):\n\n```csharp\nif (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n{\n    using var dsa = DSA.Create();\n    // native verification\n}\nelse\n{\n    // BouncyCastle fallback\n}\n```\n\n**Recommendation:** Go with BouncyCastle across all platforms for consistency, especially since DSA is legacy and you're only verifying existing signatures.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d434b063-6015-45cc-b393-686e66eedd77","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue where `DSA.Create()` fails on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a known breaking change in .NET that I can explain from my knowledge.\n\nIn .NET 7+, Microsoft has been progressively removing support for older/less-secure cryptographic algorithms on platforms where the underlying OS doesn't support them well. Specifically, on macOS, Apple's Security framework doesn't natively support DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm), and .NET historically used OpenSSL on macOS for DSA operations.\n\nThe key breaking change: Starting in .NET 7 (and continuing forward), Microsoft announced that DSA would be unsupported on macOS. \n\nIn .NET 7, `DSA.Create()` on macOS started throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException`, which is the exact error the user is encountering. This breaking change has persisted through subsequent .NET versions, so upgrading to .NET 11 would maintain this behavior. and .NET likely removed the OpenSSL interop layer for DSA on macOS in a recent version, which would explain why it suddenly stopped working. Since I don't have specific details about .NET 11's changes, the most probable cause is that DSA support was dropped entirely on macOS due to the shift away from legacy cryptographic algorithms.\n\nFor a workaround, I'd suggest either switching to BouncyCastle for cross-platform DSA support, using P/Invoke to call OpenSSL directly if it's available on the system, relying on a managed implementation if you only need signature verification, or conditionally using DSA only on Windows and Linux where it's still supported. supported on macOS in modern .NET because Apple's native crypto frameworks don't implement DSA. The `DSA.Create()` method throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.\n\nThe main workarounds are using BouncyCastle for managed DSA operations, P/Invoking into OpenSSL on macOS, or adding platform-specific logic to fall back to a managed crypto library when running on macOS while using native DSA on Windows and Linux.","outputTokens":1687,"requestId":"C430:101184:1D9F2B8:2174E8A:6A07C929"},"id":"cdd453cc-4668-47a3-b561-0bc8aee9d903","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:32:56.558Z","parentId":"bbff8ae1-514d-496b-83fa-1bea5805cf8b"}
